     On this disk you should find an excellent picture ripping program. 
When you first of all look at it, it is hard to believe that it was in 
fact coded in GFA Version 2. The idea for this first came about when I 
received a copy of Cracking Graph written by Black Angel. Cracking graph 
allowed you to load in a program and search through it looking for degas 
.PI1 pictures. Unfortunately you could not save the picture once you had 
found it, unless you had Multiface (which is complete shit, don't buy 
it!), or similar. The Doc file said to use a screen saving utility, but 
none of the ones we tried worked. So, my friend decided he would code 
something similar to Cracking Graph, but improve it in many ways. I 
pessimistically told him that he was being stupid, because he would 
not be able to do it, because he had never programmed anything before. 
Half an hour later he presented me with a copy of Camera Version 1. It 
was a very simple piece of software, but it was reliable and did it's job 
well. I congratulated him and apologised for my lack of confidence in 
him. Since then Camera has gone through many improvements. The first 
version allowed you to scroll through a program and save any picture you 
found. You were then asked whether you wanted the default palette or the 
picture palette. Now, with Camera Version 1.4 you can save the colours 
the picture is in at the time of saving, change screen resolution, toggle 
between 50hz and 60hz, change screen width, delete a file and even format 
a disk. All this using GFA Version 2 and it's free with Maggie 7. What 
more can you ask for? More versions? Easy, just send œ5.00 registration 
fee to the address shown in Camera.Doc and you can receive Camera Version 
2.0 and any further updates. We ask you to supply your own disk and 
postage. I have already seen Camera Version 2.0 and I can assure you, it 
is very good. It will only be available to subscibers, as will any other 
updates. At the moment, it is only possible to rip degas .pi1 pictures, 
but the author hopes to change this soon. There may even be a little tune 
playing away while you rip in further versions! I have found Camera very 
useful for ripping graphics from Maggie, Automation menus, etc, etc . . . 
