Never let it be said that I am a biased bloke. I have given Camera a well 
deserved plug, so now it's time to plug Ripper 3.1 by New Mode of Delta 
Force. Sammy Joe of TLB sent me this piece of software about a week ago. 
At first I was a bit apprehensive about it, but now it is a vital part of 
my software collection. The first thing you have to get used to is the 
fact that it was written on a German keyboard. This is O.K. if you have a 
German keyboard, but a bit annoying if, like me, you have an English  
keyboard. This little bug just swaps the 'Y' and 'Z' keys around. Once 
you get used to it, it is no problem. The other bug is the non-
compatibility with the STE. It still works, but the screen is affected. 
     Ripper is bootsector driven, which enables you to scroll through 
memory rather than a program. It is activated by simply pressing the 
reset button. This effectively means that you can rip from almost any 
game or demo. Obviously, it is a problem if the demo has a reset demo! I 
have already managed to rip pictures from B.I.G. Demo, Whattaheck Demo, 
and various commercial titles. It works on the same principle as Camera, 
but of course it is bootsector driven. You can also choose the palette 
using Ripper, but this can sometimes be a long and sometimes difficult 
process. We once spent over half an hour trying to get the right 
palette for the title picture for Shadow of The Beast! It also saves in 
.NEO format, which takes up more room than a .pi1 picture. I wonder why 
it saves in Neochrome format? New Mode must know the author of Neochrome 
or something! Well that's about it for this review. All we have to do now 
is the summaries.

